Successive COVID-19 Waves Analysis

Imane Krourou

Part 1

Introduction

This study focuses on analyzing how hospitals adapted and recovered post-COVID surges, specifically focusing on ICU bed capacities and their impact on mortality rates during the waves of the pandemic. This research is crucial for understanding the effectiveness of hospital responses and preparing for future surges.

Methods

This study makes use of a longitudinal analysis on the Metro-level Covid ActNow (CAN) data from January 1, 2021 to March 1, 2022 by using variables such as the number of new cases announced, ICU bed capacity, COVID-19 admissions to the ICU, mortality rates, and general hospital bed capacities. To take a closer look at these trends, the data will be segmented into distinct waves, which will allow the examination of changes in performance of hospitals in provision of in-demand beds over time.

Results

Data preparation

This dataset was first subset to select only the variables which were directly applicable to this study. These included the date, new cases, Covid-19 related deaths, information hospital bed capacities and ICU bed capacities.

Here I defined the base date and then subsetted the data based on the common base date

Trend analysis.

Here I plotted ICU capacities and mortality trends over time

Based on the trend analysis of new cases in Fig. 1, about four Covid-19 surges can be recognized throughout the period under consideration. Similar to the number of ICU bed capacity displayed on Fig. 3, the overall number of hospital beds as shown in Fig. 2 looks to drop approaching the year 2022. On the other hand, as Fig. 4 illustrates, the number of deaths has increased steadily during the monitoring period.

Covid-19 new cases surge waves between 1st January 2021 and 31st January 2022

It looks that the initial rise in 2021 lasted until the middle of February, and then there will be a second, lesser surge from the middle of February to the middle of May. Between July and October, there is another spike in new cases, with the biggest spike occurring from the middle of November until the end of the observation period. To show the surges, a new wave variable was established.
So I created a new variable wave indicating the wave for each observation

The number of new cases (avg_newCases), total hospital bed capacity (avg_BedsCapacity), ICU bed capacity (avg_ICUBedsCapacity), average bed usage (avg_bedsusage), and average ICU COVID usage (avg_ICUcovidusage) during each surge wave are among the important metrics whose average values are displayed in the table. According to the data, the most catastrophic wave of recorded Covid-19-related deaths occurred between November 2021 and February 2022. Notably, despite the fact that this wave had the highest number of new cases per day, the average ICU bed capacity was declining in comparison to the prior waves. This shows that the ICU bed capacity numbers did not improve, despite the increased Covid-19 usage in the previous waves. This might have contributed to the steadily increasing reported Covid-19 related mortality. This is clearly shown in Fig. 5.

Intervention analysis: The impact of vaccinations and ICU beds capacity on new daily deaths

This section aims to explore the impact of two crucial factors, the ratios of the completed vaccinations and ICU bed capacities, on daily COVID-19-related deaths. Understanding the effectiveness of these interventions is vital for informed decision-making and future pandemic preparedness. The distribution of the number of new daily deaths as displayed by the boxplot in Fig. 9 shows that outliers were the order of the day across all waves. The largest number of deaths in any one particular day were recorded during the third wave.

The correlation matrix reveals weak associations between the variables. Specifically, completed vaccinations and ICU bed capacity ratio show a negligible positive correlation (0.15), while the correlation between new daily deaths and both completed vaccinations (-0.05) and ICU bed capacity ratio (0.09) is very weak. These results suggest limited linear relationships, consequently implying that non-linear methods might be more suitable for modeling these variables, or there might be need to stratify the data into the various waves before computing the correlation.

Part 2

Introduction

In addition to examining hospital adaptations and ICU bed capacities, it is essential to understand the broader social determinants that may have influenced healthcare outcomes during the COVID-19 pandemic. This part of the study extends the analysis to consider the impact of county-level social determinants, such as the Area Deprivation Index (ADI) and Medicaid coverage, alongside vaccination rates, on local hospital and ICU capacities. Social determinants of health, including socioeconomic status, access to healthcare, and community resources, play a crucial role in shaping health outcomes. The Area Deprivation Index (ADI) provides a comprehensive measure of socioeconomic disadvantage, incorporating factors such as income, education, employment, and housing quality.

Data Processing

#Data Sources and Integration

In this study, we integrated data from multiple sources to comprehensively analyze the impact of social determinants and vaccination rates on local hospital and ICU capacities during the COVID-19 pandemic. I obtained the data US_2022_ADI_Census_Block_Group_v4_0_1.csv data from (https://www.neighborhoodatlas.medicine.wisc.edu/).

The following steps outline the detailed data processing and integration procedures:

Reading the Datasets:

Social Determinants Data: The social determinants data, which includes the Area Deprivation Index (ADI) and other socioeconomic factors, was obtained from the file US_2022_ADI_Census_Block_Group_v4_0_1.csv. This dataset provides valuable insights into the socioeconomic status of various regions, incorporating factors such as income, education, employment, and housing quality. The data was read using the fread function from the data.table package in R to ensure efficient handling of large datasets. CBSAs Timeseries Data: The timeseries data for Core-Based Statistical Areas (CBSAs), which includes detailed information on hospital and ICU bed usage, COVID-19 cases and deaths, and vaccination rates, was sourced from the file cbsas.timeseries.csv. This dataset tracks the temporal evolution of the pandemic and healthcare utilization across different metropolitan areas.

Extracting County Codes:

To facilitate the merging of datasets, county codes were extracted from the respective FIPS codes in both datasets. In the social determinants data, the 5-digit FIPS codes were parsed to obtain the county codes. In the CBSAs timeseries data, the 12-digit FIPS codes were similarly processed to extract the relevant county codes. This step ensured that data from both sources could be accurately aligned based on geographic identifiers.

Data Cleaning:

Before merging the datasets, it was essential to ensure that the relevant columns in the CBSAs timeseries data were in the appropriate numeric format. This conversion was crucial for accurate data analysis and integration. The columns converted included: actuals.hospitalBeds.currentUsageTotal: Total current usage of hospital beds. actuals.icuBeds.currentUsageTotal: Total current usage of ICU beds. actuals.vaccinationsCompleted: Total number of completed vaccinations.

Filtering Data:

To maintain the integrity and accuracy of the analysis, rows with missing values (NA) in key columns were filtered out. Specifically, the analysis focused on complete cases for the following columns: actuals.hospitalBeds.currentUsageTotal actuals.icuBeds.currentUsageTotal actuals.vaccinationsCompleted

Merging Datasets:

The key socioeconomic variable, ADI_NATRANK from the social determinants data, was converted to a numeric format to ensure compatibility with the CBSAs timeseries data. The filtered CBSAs timeseries data was then merged with the social determinants data using the cbind function in R, aligning the datasets by county codes. This step enabled the integration of socioeconomic information with healthcare utilization data, facilitating a comprehensive analysis of the impact of social determinants on hospital performance and pandemic outcomes.

The regression models aim to predict hospital bed usage and ICU bed usage based on two predictor variables: vaccinations completed (actuals.vaccinationsCompleted) and the Area Deprivation Index (ADI_NATRANK). In both models, the intercept represents the expected value of the outcome variable when all predictor variables are zero. The coefficients indicate the estimated change in the outcome variable for a one-unit increase in the corresponding predictor, holding other predictors constant. For hospital bed usage, each additional completed vaccination is associated with an estimated increase of 0.00275 in hospital bed usage, while each unit increase in the Area Deprivation Index is associated with a decrease of 0.0516 in hospital bed usage, although the latter is not statistically significant (p = 0.419).

Similarly, for ICU bed usage, each additional completed vaccination is associated with an estimated increase of 0.0003175 in ICU bed usage, while the effect of the Area Deprivation Index is not statistically significant (p = 0.657). The models have high multiple R-squared values (0.7106 for hospital bed usage and 0.6378 for ICU bed usage), indicating that a substantial proportion of the variability in bed usage is explained by the predictor variables. Additionally, the extremely low p-values for the F-statistics (< 0.0001) indicate that both models are statistically significant, suggesting that the predictors jointly have a significant effect on bed usage.

The provided ANOVA output assesses the significance of the predictor variables, actuals.vaccinationsCompleted and ADI_NATRANK, in explaining the variability in hospital bed usage (first output) and ICU bed usage (second output), respectively.

For the hospital model:

The sum of squares represents the variation attributed to each predictor variable and the residual variation (unexplained by the predictors). The degrees of freedom indicate the number of independent pieces of information used to estimate the variation for each predictor and the residuals. The residual standard error represents the average amount that the observed hospital bed usage deviates from the predicted values. The estimated effects may be unbalanced, suggesting potential variability or non-normality in the data. 6384 observations were deleted due to missingness.

For the ICU model:

Similarly, the sum of squares, degrees of freedom, and residual standard error are provided for the predictor variables and residuals. The estimated effects may also be unbalanced. 6384 observations were deleted due to missingness. Overall, these ANOVA outputs help assess the significance of the predictor variables in explaining the variability in hospital and ICU bed usage, providing insights into their contributions to the models.

Discussion

The results of the analyses shed light on the dynamics of hospital performance during successive waves of the COVID-19 pandemic, as well as the influence of social determinants and vaccination rates on hospital and ICU bed capacities. In Part 1, the summary data of surge waves revealed notable variations in average new cases, bed capacities, ICU bed capacities, deaths, and the usage of beds and ICU beds. Interestingly, the t-test results indicated no significant difference in ICU bed capacity between the first and fourth waves, despite observed increasing trends between these waves. Moreover, the ANOVA results from the fitted multiple linear regression model underscored the collective impact of Covid-19 surge waves and other factors, such as ICU bed capacity, on COVID-19 deaths. Similarly, in Part 2, regression analysis illuminated the relationship between vaccinations, social determinants, and hospital/ICU bed usage, offering insights into the complex interplay of these factors in shaping healthcare capacity during the pandemic. These findings underscore the multifaceted nature of pandemic response efforts and highlight the importance of considering various determinants when assessing hospital readiness and resource allocation strategies.

Conclusion

This study provides a comprehensive analysis of hospitals bed capacity performance during different phases of the Covid-19 pandemic, incorporating insights from both Part 1 and Part 2 analyses. The results revealed a concerning trend of declining ICU bed capacity, contrary to the anticipated increase needed to accommodate the rising number of patients amidst the surge in new daily cases. This discrepancy underscores the critical importance of maintaining and possibly enhancing ICU capacities over time, particularly during successive waves of pandemics. By addressing this disparity, healthcare systems can better adapt and respond to the evolving challenges posed by such crises. Moreover, the insights drawn from both parts of the study can significantly inform future healthcare strategies, emphasizing the necessity for sustained preparedness and effective resource allocation in anticipation of and response to pandemics. By incorporating these findings into policy making and planning efforts, healthcare systems can enhance their resilience and capacity to mitigate the impact of future public health emergencies.
